18:18.320 --> 18:22.560
took the scattering amplitude for two gluons coming in

18:22.560 --> 18:25.520
at high energy and four gluons going out at low energy.

18:25.520 --> 18:27.120
So that kind of scattering thing.

18:27.120 --> 18:30.160
So it's like apparently for people who are into this,

18:30.160 --> 18:31.920
that's sort of something that happens so often

18:31.920 --> 18:34.240
you need to be able to find it and get rid of those

18:34.240 --> 18:36.080
because you already know about that and need to.

18:36.080 --> 18:37.120
So you needed to compute them.

18:37.120 --> 18:39.760
It was billions of terms and they couldn't do it.

18:39.760 --> 18:41.920
Even for the supercomputers couldn't do that

18:41.920 --> 18:44.400
for the many billions or millions of times per second

18:44.400 --> 18:45.040
they needed to do it.

18:45.040 --> 18:48.720
So they bagged, the experimentals bagged the theorists

18:48.720 --> 18:50.560
and please can you, you got it.

18:51.200 --> 18:53.040
So Park and Taylor took the billions of terms,

18:53.040 --> 18:57.440
hundreds of pages and miraculously turned it into nine.

18:58.000 --> 19:00.000
And then a little bit later they guessed

19:00.000 --> 19:02.400
one term expression that turned out to be equivalent.

19:02.400 --> 19:07.120
So billions of terms reduced to one term

19:07.120 --> 19:10.720
that's so-called famous Park-Taylor formula, 1986.

19:10.720 --> 19:13.840
And that was like, okay, where did that come from?

19:13.920 --> 19:16.560
What, this is a pointer into a deep realm

19:17.200 --> 19:20.560
beyond space and time, but no one, I mean,

19:20.560 --> 19:21.600
what can you do with it?

19:21.600 --> 19:23.040
And they thought maybe it was a one-off,

19:23.040 --> 19:25.760
but then other formulas started coming up

19:25.760 --> 19:28.400
and then eventually Neymar, Connie, Hamad and his team

19:28.400 --> 19:30.160
found this thing called the amplituhedron

19:30.160 --> 19:32.160
which really sort of captures the whole,

19:32.880 --> 19:34.320
a big part of the whole ball of wax.

19:35.600 --> 19:37.840
I'm sure they would say, no, there's plenty more to do.

19:37.840 --> 19:40.320
So I won't say they did it all by any means.

19:40.320 --> 19:42.640
They're looking at the cosmological polytope as well.

19:42.640 --> 19:48.880
So what's remarkable to me is that two pillars of modern science,

19:49.680 --> 19:52.160
quantum field theory with gravity on the one hand,

19:52.800 --> 19:54.560
and evolution by natural selection on the other.

19:55.440 --> 19:58.240
Just in the last 20 years have very clearly said

19:58.960 --> 20:00.480
space-time has had a good run.

20:01.040 --> 20:03.680
Reductionism has been a fantastic methodology.

20:03.680 --> 20:05.600
So we had a great ontology of space-time,

20:05.600 --> 20:07.200
a great methodology of reductionism.

20:07.920 --> 20:09.280
Now it's time for a new trick.

20:10.640 --> 20:12.080
But now you need to go deeper.

20:12.080 --> 20:15.760
And show, by the way, this doesn't mean we throw away everything we've done,

20:15.760 --> 20:16.560
not by a long shot.

20:17.200 --> 20:20.880
Every new idea that we come up with beyond space-time

20:20.880 --> 20:23.200
must project precisely into space-time.

20:23.200 --> 20:26.480
And it better give us back everything that we know and love in space-time

20:26.480 --> 20:27.680
or generalizations.

20:28.640 --> 20:30.800
Or it's not going to be taken seriously and it shouldn't be.

20:30.800 --> 20:34.560
So we have a strong constraint on whatever we're going to do

20:34.560 --> 20:35.440
beyond space-time.

20:35.440 --> 20:37.520
It needs to project into space-time.

20:37.520 --> 20:39.280
And whatever this deeper theory is,

20:39.280 --> 20:42.720
it may not itself have evolution by natural selection.

20:42.720 --> 20:44.320
This may not be part of this deeper realm.

20:44.320 --> 20:47.440
But when we take whatever that thing is beyond space-time

20:47.440 --> 20:49.120
and project it into space-time,

20:49.120 --> 20:51.680
it has to look like evolution by natural selection.

20:51.680 --> 20:52.320
Or it's wrong.

20:52.960 --> 20:57.360
So that's a strong constraint on this work.

20:57.360 --> 21:04.160
So even the evolution by natural selection and quantum field theory

21:05.120 --> 21:10.640
could be interfaces into something that doesn't look anything like,

21:11.520 --> 21:12.080
like you mentioned.

21:12.080 --> 21:14.800
I mean, it's interesting to think that evolution might be

21:15.360 --> 21:18.160
a very crappy interface into something much deeper.

21:18.160 --> 21:18.880
That's right.

21:18.880 --> 21:23.040
They're both telling us that the framework that you've had can only go so far.

21:23.040 --> 21:24.000
And it has to stop.

21:24.000 --> 21:25.440
And there's something beyond.

21:25.440 --> 21:29.040
And that framework, the very framework that is space and time itself.

21:29.040 --> 21:33.040
Now, of course, evolution by natural selection is not telling us

21:33.840 --> 21:36.240
about like Einstein's relativistic space time.

21:36.240 --> 21:38.240
So that was another question you asked a little bit earlier.

21:38.240 --> 21:41.600
It's telling us more about our perceptual space and time,

21:42.400 --> 21:49.040
which we have used as the basis for creating first a Newtonian space versus time

21:49.600 --> 21:53.440
as a mathematical extension of our perceptions.

21:53.440 --> 21:56.560
And then Einstein then took that and extended it even further.

21:56.560 --> 21:58.960
So the relationship between what evolution is telling us

21:58.960 --> 22:00.960
and what the physicists are telling us is that,

22:00.960 --> 22:09.440
in some sense, the Newton and Einstein space time are formulated as sort of

22:10.160 --> 22:12.400
rigorous extensions of our perceptual space,

22:14.080 --> 22:19.040
making it mathematically rigorous and laying out the symmetries that they find there.

22:19.040 --> 22:20.720
So that's sort of the relationship between them.

22:20.720 --> 22:27.040
So it's the perceptual space time that evolution is telling us is just a user interface effectively.

22:27.680 --> 22:30.640
And then the physicists are finding that even the mathematical extension

22:30.960 --> 22:34.880
of that into the Einsteinian formulation has to be,

22:34.880 --> 22:36.880
as well, not the final story.

22:36.880 --> 22:38.080
There's something deeper.

22:38.080 --> 22:43.120
So let me ask you about reductionism and interfaces.

22:43.120 --> 22:49.040
As we march forward from Newtonian physics to quantum mechanics,

22:49.920 --> 22:53.280
these are all, in your view, interfaces.

22:56.160 --> 22:58.640
Are we getting closer to objective reality?

22:59.280 --> 23:04.000
How do we know if these interfaces in the process of science,

23:04.800 --> 23:09.680
the reason we like those interfaces is because they're predictive of some aspects,

23:09.680 --> 23:12.880
strongly predictive about some aspects of our reality.

23:14.080 --> 23:19.440
Is that completely deviating from our understanding of that reality?

23:19.440 --> 23:21.920
Or is it helping us get closer and closer and closer?

23:22.640 --> 23:27.200
Well, of course, one critical constraint on all of our theories is that they are empirically tested

23:27.200 --> 23:30.800
and pass the experiments that we have for them.

23:30.800 --> 23:34.400
So no one's arguing against experiments being important

23:34.400 --> 23:40.560
and wanting to test all of our current theories and any new theories on that.

23:40.560 --> 23:43.520
So that's all there.

23:44.240 --> 23:50.800
But we have good reason to believe that science will never get a theory of everything.

23:52.320 --> 23:53.520
Everything, everything.

23:53.520 --> 23:55.680
Everything, everything, right, a final theory of everything, right?

23:56.320 --> 23:59.600
I think that my, my own take is for what it's worth is that

23:59.600 --> 24:03.040
girdles in completeness theorem sort of points us in that direction,

24:03.040 --> 24:08.480
that even with mathematics, any finite axiomatization that's

24:08.480 --> 24:10.400
sophisticated enough to be able to do arithmetic,

24:11.040 --> 24:14.160
it's easy to show that there'll be statements that are true,

24:14.160 --> 24:18.800
that can't be proven, can't be deduced from within that framework.

24:19.440 --> 24:21.840
And if you add the new statements to your axioms,

24:21.840 --> 24:24.160
then there'll be always new statements that are true,

24:24.160 --> 24:26.000
but can't be proven with a new axiom system.

24:26.880 --> 24:32.560
And the best scientific theories in physics, for example,

24:32.560 --> 24:34.960
and also now evolution, are mathematical.

24:34.960 --> 24:37.440
So our theories are going to be, they're going to have their own assumptions,

24:38.400 --> 24:41.600
and they'll be mathematically precise.

24:41.600 --> 24:44.320
And there'll be theories perhaps of everything except those assumptions,

24:44.320 --> 24:46.960
because assumptions are, we say,

24:46.960 --> 24:48.160
please grant me these assumptions.

24:48.160 --> 24:50.640
If you grant me these assumptions, then I can explain this other stuff.

24:51.440 --> 24:57.520
But so you have the assumptions that are like miracles,

24:57.520 --> 24:59.360
as far as the theory is concerned, they're not explained,

24:59.360 --> 25:01.600
they're the starting points for explanation.

25:01.600 --> 25:04.240
And then you have the mathematical structure of the theory itself,

25:04.240 --> 25:06.880
which will have the girdle limits.

25:07.520 --> 25:16.400
And so my take is that reality, whatever it is, is always going to transcend

25:16.400 --> 25:22.320
any conceptual theory that we can come up with.

25:22.320 --> 25:24.000
There's always going to be mystery at the edges.

25:27.520 --> 25:29.360
Contradictions and all that kind of stuff.

25:29.360 --> 25:29.680
Okay.

