some kind of important test for the theories?

29:10.400 --> 29:15.760
Does it mean that anything goes in scientific theory, but if we don't see the truth,

29:15.760 --> 29:18.080
is there no way to tether our theories and test them?

29:18.560 --> 29:24.080
And I think there's no problem there.

29:24.800 --> 29:29.520
We can only test things in terms of what we can measure with our senses in space and time.

29:29.520 --> 29:36.000
So we're going to have to continue to do experiments, but we're going to understand

29:36.000 --> 29:38.240
a little bit differently what those experiments are.

29:38.880 --> 29:45.600
We had thought that when we see a pointer on some machine in an experiment,

29:45.600 --> 29:49.920
that the machine exists, the pointer exists, and the values exist even when no one

29:49.920 --> 29:52.640
is looking at them, and that they're an objective truth.

29:52.640 --> 29:54.880
And our best theories are telling us no.

29:56.400 --> 30:01.840
Pointers are just pointers, and that's what you have to rely on for making your judgments.

30:02.800 --> 30:09.840
But even the pointers themselves are not the objective reality.

30:10.480 --> 30:15.840
So and I think Gertl is telling us that not that anything goes, but

30:16.800 --> 30:20.800
as you develop new axiom systems, you will find out what goes within that axiom system

30:21.520 --> 30:23.600
and what testable predictions you can make.

30:23.600 --> 30:25.680
So I don't think we're untethered.

30:25.680 --> 30:27.840
We continue to do experiments.

30:27.840 --> 30:32.960
What I think we won't have that we want is a conceptual understanding

30:33.920 --> 30:36.640
that gives us a theory of everything that's final and complete.

30:37.440 --> 30:42.720
I think that this is, to put it another way, this is job security for scientists.

30:43.920 --> 30:45.120
Our job will never be done.

30:45.120 --> 30:46.720
It's job security for neuroscience.

30:47.600 --> 30:50.640
