31:01.680 --> 31:03.680
We have to say what is beyond space-time?

31:04.640 --> 31:05.680
What is going on?

31:05.680 --> 31:08.240
What is a dynamical system beyond space-time?

31:08.240 --> 31:10.480
That when we project it into Einstein space-time,

31:10.480 --> 31:13.920
gives us things that look like neurons and neural networks and synapses.

31:15.200 --> 31:16.400
So we have to reverse engineer.

31:16.400 --> 31:18.880
So there's going to be lots more work for neuroscience.

31:18.880 --> 31:23.760
It's going to be far more complicated and difficult and challenging.

31:23.760 --> 31:24.960
But that's wonderful.

31:24.960 --> 31:25.920
That's what we need to do.

31:25.920 --> 31:29.280
We thought neurons exist when they are perceived and they don't.

31:29.280 --> 31:31.920
In the same way that if I show you, when I say they don't exist,

31:31.920 --> 31:33.360
I should be very, very concrete.

31:34.320 --> 31:40.400
If I draw on a piece of paper a little sketch of something that is called the necker cube,

31:40.400 --> 31:42.640
it's just a little line drawing of a cube.

31:42.640 --> 31:43.920
It's on a flat piece of paper.

31:43.920 --> 31:48.320
If I execute it well and I show it to you, you'll see a 3D cube and you'll see it flip.

31:48.320 --> 31:49.680
Sometimes you'll see one face in front.

31:49.680 --> 31:51.120
Sometimes you'll see the other face in front.

31:51.760 --> 31:54.960
But if I ask you, which face is in front when you don't look?

31:57.200 --> 32:00.320
The answer is, well, neither face is in front because there's no cube.

32:01.200 --> 32:02.560
This is a flat piece of paper.

32:03.200 --> 32:07.520
So when you look at the piece of paper, you perceptually create the cube.

32:08.400 --> 32:13.120
And when you look at it, then you fix one face to be in front and one face to be in front.

32:13.120 --> 32:15.920
So that's what I mean when I say it doesn't exist.

32:15.920 --> 32:18.080
Space time itself is like the cube.

32:18.080 --> 32:21.840
It's a data structure that your sensory systems construct,

32:21.840 --> 32:27.280
whatever your sensory systems mean now, because we now have to even take that for granted.

32:27.280 --> 32:30.720
But there are perceptions that you construct on the fly.

32:31.280 --> 32:33.920
And they're data structures and the computer science says,

32:33.920 --> 32:35.600
and you garbage collect them when you don't need them.

32:35.600 --> 32:37.360
So you create them and garbage collect them.

32:37.360 --> 32:45.440
But is it possible that it's mapped well in some concrete, predictable way to objective reality?

32:45.440 --> 32:50.560
The sheet of paper, the two-dimensional space, or we can talk about space time,

32:51.200 --> 32:58.480
maps in some way that we maybe don't yet understand, but we'll one day understand

32:58.560 --> 32:59.520
what that mapping is.

32:59.520 --> 33:00.800
But it maps reliably.

33:00.800 --> 33:02.320
It is tethered in that way.

